{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":9898,"record_hash":"sha256:41eb3b476e287673aab77d0fc792ddfd47d8659ae23a88cbc4647aed8c436d9f","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:35:59.126Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 081889\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 2375\nOutput:\n# Agent Session Handoff Design\n\nThis note sketches the handoff feature that sits above the `but-agentlog`\nprimitives. It is intentionally not an implementation contract yet.\n\n## Goal\n\nLet a developer continue work from one machine, agent, or provider session in\nanother machine, agent, or provider session.\n\nThe target experience:\n\n1. work happens on a branch with agentlog capture enabled\n2. GitMeta sync moves captured agentlog data with the repository metadata\n3. another machine checks out or switches to the branch\n4. the user asks an agent to catch up\n5. the agent uses GitButler commands to discover and read relevant prior session\n   context\n6. the new agent continues with enough context to be useful, without pretending\n   it has natively resumed the old provider session\n\nThis is contextual handoff, not exact provider-native replay.\n\n## Current Building Blocks\n\nThe primitive layer can already provide the facts a handoff flow needs:\n\n- durable project-scoped sessions\n- capture turns within sessions\n- ordered transcript records within each turn\n- environment observations for each turn\n- GitMeta sync of the stored data\n- verified lookup of sessions related to a branch, review, or change\n- bounded hydration of related turn windows\n\nThat is enough to design an agent-facing workflow without adding product-shaped\nstate to `but-agentlog`.\n\n## Design Bias\n\nThe agent should get tools, not a generated handoff essay.\n\nThat said, raw transcript access alone is not enough. Once sessions include\nsubagents, compactions, large backfills, and repeated captures, asking the next\nagent to infer everything from a giant transcript is brittle and expensive.\n\nThe useful middle ground is:\n\n- deterministic orientation commands\n- bounded transcript hydration\n- stable machine-readable JSON\n- enough metadata to let the agent choose what to read next\n- optional human-readable output for manual debugging\n\nDo not bake a model-generated\n[TRUNCATED]\nirst surface.\n\n## Agent-Facing Workflow\n\nA good first workflow is deliberately small:\n\n```text\nbut agentlog sessions branch <branch>\nbut agentlog timeline <session-key> [--turns N]\nbut agentlog related-detail branch <branch> <session-key> [--context-before N] [--context-after N]\n```\n\nThe exact names can change, but the shape matters:\n\n1. discover related sessions for the current target\n2. inspect a compact session/turn outline\n3. hydrate only the windows that look useful\n\nThe user prompt can be simple:\n\n```text\nCheck whether there are prior agent sessions related to this branch and catch up.\n```\n\nA future skill can teach agents this sequence, but the CLI should be sensible\nwithout the skill.\n\n## Discovery Output\n\nThe discovery command should answer:\n\n- which sessions are related to this branch/review/change?\n- which turns caused that relationship?\n- how recent are they?\n- how much data would reading them cost?\n- which agent/provider/model created them?\n- are they mostly one large backfill or incremental ongoing work?\n\nMachine-readable output should include at least:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_kind\": \"branch\",\n  \"target_key\": \"ref:refs/heads/example\",\n  \"sessions\": [\n    {\n      \"session_key\": \"sha256-...\",\n      \"updated_at\": \"2026-05-20T18:12:21.645Z\",\n      \"source_count\": 1,\n      \"turn_count\": 8,\n      \"record_count\": 5785,\n      \"related_turn_keys\": [\"sha256-...\"],\n      \"agents\": [\"codex\"],\n      \"providers\": [\"openai\"],\n      \"models\": [\"gpt-5.5\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\nThis is not a summary. It is an index card for choosing what to read.\n\n## Timeline Output\n\nThe timeline command should show turn-level structure before hydrating full\nrecords:\n\n- `turn_key`\n- `previous_turn_key`\n- `capture_kind`\n- `captured_at`\n- record count\n- environment snapshot status\n- observed branch/review/change keys\n- first and last record timestamps\n- maybe a tiny preview of first/last user text\n\nThis gives the next agent a cheap way to decide whether to read:\n\n- the latest turns\n- the highlighted related turns\n- the whole main session\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:35:59.126Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}